  3. <Assumption Ledger>

    <assumption status="<safe>">
      Ryle rejects the view that concepts are isolated mental occurrences.
    </assumption>

    <assumption status="<safe>">
      Ryle treats concept acquisition as learning what can be done with a concept.
    </assumption>

    <assumption status="<safe>">
      The square-root, prime-number, and even-number examples are operational tests, not decorative illustrations.
    </assumption>

    <assumption status="<safe>">
      "Factor, not slice" is the governing structural distinction.
    </assumption>

    <assumption status="<uncertain>">
      "Operational mastery" is a faithful modern compression of Ryle’s position, not Ryle’s own explicit term.
    </assumption>

    <assumption status="<uncertain>">
      Extending the model to AI evaluation is a contemporary extrapolation from the paper’s logic.
    </assumption>

    <assumption status="<requires-user-decision>">
      The theory may later become an assessment engine, benchmark generator, classroom diagnostic tool, or philosophical interface.
    </assumption>


